{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cd9812f1-6bd1-489a-9bdc-a18795afb1a1","content":"Since you're using **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (via `global.json`) with **MSTest 3.8.0**, you can use the built-in hang dump feature:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nThis will:\n1. Monitor each test for hangs\n2. After 5 minutes of no progress, capture a hang dump (useful for diagnosing the root cause)\n3. Terminate the hanging process\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` args from the MTP runner args. The dump file location will be printed in the output if a hang is detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"186e8128-dad6-4aae-8dea-b2754e3e4e8c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) runner via `global.json`. For MTP, the hang detection is configured via command-line options. The option is `--hang-dump-timeout` or similar.\n\nFor Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can pass `--hang-dump-timeout <duration>` to detect hangs. Let me check the exact flag name.\n\nActually, for Microsoft Testing Platform, the hang dump feature is available through `--hangdump` and `--hangdump-timeout`. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\nThe MSTest 3.8.0 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner supports hang dump via:\n\n\n- `--hangdump` to enable hang detection\n- `--hangdump-timeout <timeout>` to set the timeout\n\nSince they're using the MTP runner from `global.json`, I need to pass these flags after `--` in the `dotnet test` command, so the command would be `dotnet test -- --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m` or run it directly with `dotnet run -- --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m`.","outputTokens":434},"id":"226c6260-3511-45bf-ba9c-58729ab7cb4a","timestamp":"2026-04-07T14:20:54.346Z","parentId":"3147c0aa-06bc-4664-8c44-b703c1c4b948"}
